$LNG['questions'][2][1]['body']		= <<<BODY
<h3>Raids:</h3>
<p>A raid is an attack on another players planet undertaken in order to acquire their resources. If an attack is successful, up to 50% of the resources on the target planet may be taken by the attacking fleet as plunder. There are several types of attacks such as</p>:
<ul>
<li>Inactive Raids</li>
<li>ACS(Alliance Combat System)</li>
<li>Intercepting a fleet</li>
</ul>
<h3>Inactive Raids:</h3>
<p>This is one of the easiest and least risky raids in which you can make resources quickly and learn the basics of raiding. Often you won't be able to attack any active players around you as most of them will be online, or already fleetsaving (explained in the next section). However you can raid inactive players as they are not likely to come online (inactive meaning they have not logged in for more than 7 days). Farming inactives is not as suspenseful as
attacking active players but nevertheless it is a good way of working around risky and time consuming attacks. Note that the bashing rule does not apply to inactives.</p>
<h3>ACS:</h3>
<p>The Alliance Combat System (or ACS) allows for friends and alliance members to temporarily combine their fleets to attack or defend a target that either might not have been able to attack or defend alone. Ensure you take part in an ACS with players you can trust as any fleet participating in an ACS can be recalled without knowledge of other participants. An Alliance Depot is not a prerequisite to attack or defend a planet with ACS.</p>
<h3>Intercepting a fleet:</h3>
<p>This is where it gets tricky. How to obtain suitable targets? Through spying, you may observe idling fleets on planets and moons, but the question remains of whether the player (which the fleets belong to) is online. This can be observed in Galaxy View  by an asterisk (*) or the displayed minutes since they were last active. Experienced fleeters rely on a wealth of intelligence beyond these basics, and are often capable of crashing (destroying) fleets returning from fleetsaves.</p>
BODY;
$LNG['questions'][2][2]['title']	= 'Fleetsave';
$LNG['questions'][2][2]['body']		= <<<BODY
<h3>Strategies of Deterrence</h3>
<p>A large amount of defence can deter raiding fleets, but if large amounts of resources are stored on the planet it will lure in opportunists as the benefits outweigh the costs. To accomplish a successful raid, the attacking fleet must destroy all opposing ships and defences on the planet. In contrast to ships, defences do not leave a debris field on destruction, but are repaired to 70% capacity after the combat. </p>
<p>In addition the Interplanetary Missile destroys defences remotely. As one might expect, missiles are built at a cost and are expended in a single attack. A well-planned attack with several missiles targeted at specific defence infrastructure is likely to reduce the damage dealt to a raiding fleet significantly. Nevertheless, planets are not entirely vulnerable to missile attacks. Interceptor Missiles shoot down Interplanetary Missiles one for one, and are more numerous (per Missile Silo level) and are produced at less cost.</p>
<p>Espionage Research allows a player to 'spy' on a planet's resources, idling fleet, defences, buildings and research; depending on the level of Espionage gained, and the number of spy probes used. Espionage at higher levels also provides more information, i.e. intelligence about an attacking fleet; examine the details about Espionage (by clicking its picture) in the Research tab for more information.</p>
<h3>Fleetsave</h3>
<p>Fleetsaving is a key component of NULLSPACE, and the majority of games in this genre, and without an understanding of fleetsaving, new players will justifiably feel like quitting altogether. Ensure that you understand the concept: Fleetsaving loads up your fleet with your planets' resources and keeps your fleet and resources in space - all invulnerable during that period - while you're offline: working, sleeping, or any other activity that will result in a lapse of attention.<br>The first method of fleetsaving is "Mission Hold and Recall". This is the action of deploying your fleet to a planet in the area for a potential holding pattern. The key is to recall the fleet before it reaches the planet which makes the fleet's return trip duration difficult to predict for other players looking for prey. In order for the mission to be of a sufficient duration for long offline times, i.e. sleeping, the fleet speed must be reduced ultimately as low as 10%. Be aware that the return trip duration will be equal to the elapsed time up to the point you recall.</p>
<p>Another common and safer method is sending the fleet on a Recycle mission in which recylers are a necessary component of the fleet. Recyclers are comparatively slow, and will prolong the return time of the fleetsave.</p>
<p>The most foolproof of fleetsaving methods is Moon to Moon Deploy missions, in which no players are able to scan (via Phalanx) any missions that occur between moons. However this entails the prerequisite of having more than one moon, and may only be possible later in the game.</p>
BODY;
$LNG['questions'][2][3]['title']	= 'Moons';
$LNG['questions'][2][3]['body']		= <<<BODY
<p>A moon may form when a field of debris has at least 100,000 units, which then leads to a 1% chance of the formation of a moon. With increasing amounts of debris, the chances of moon formation increases, with a maximum chance of 20% and no higher.</p>
<h3>General</h3>
<p>Moons may also be given custom names like planets, and start with the default name: 'Moon'. You can have more than one moon, but only one per planet. One of greatest advantages of having moons is the inability to Phalanx Scan Moon to Moon fleetsaves. On the Moon, a base must be first built for very limited fields (building capacity), and may be followed by the building of Robotics Factories, a Shipyard, a Phalanx Sensor and ultimately, a Jumpgate.</p>
<h3>Sizes of moons</h3>
<p>The moon may be created depending on the quantity of debris generated in a battle. In a lot of cases, friendly players and/or alliances attempt to produce moons intentionally. This most commonly accomplished by destroying 1667 Light Cargos/Light Fighters in a battle on the targeted 'moon-less' planet that results in the maximum chance of 20%. Light Cargos are recommended for the ease of their destruction, and Light Fighters for lower costs of crystal to produce them.</p><p>In a moonshot, the targeted planet should have defences and/or fleet on the planet sufficient to destroy 1667 of these ships. Using the Simulator will inform players on the sufficiency of their defensive capacity to destroy the incoming fleet.</p><p>The anticipated amount of debris following a battle will determine the size of moon around your planet should it form by chance.</p><p>The size of moons created from probabilities between 1% and 19% are of random size, but for a probability of 20% ,the moon will have a diameter of at least 8000 km.<br>Regular moons never exceed 8944 km in diameter.</p>
<h3>Construction</h3>
<p>The three specific buildings on the moon are:</p>
<ul><li><p><b>Moon Base</b><br>Used to create three new fields, in which further buildings may be built. Be aware that building further Moon Bases - i.e. for more fields - requires one field to be reserved for each further Moon Base built.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Sensor Phalanx</b><br>Used to see the Mission activities of any fleet interacting with or deploying from the scanned planet. The target planet needs to be within range of the Sensor Phalanx, of which its range increases with the building level of it. Sensor Phalanx is unable to scan Moons.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Jumpgate</b><br>This is used for transferring fleet from one moon to another instantaneously. Be aware that the jumpgate does not permit the fleet to carry any resources through it.</p></li></ul>
<p>Here is a sample progression of the development on a Moon:<br>
<b>Legend:</b><br>
MB – Moon Base<br>
PS – Phalanx Sensor<br>
JG – Jumpgate<br>
RB – Robotics Factory</p>
<p>MB1 – RB1 – RB2 – MB2 – PS1 – RB3 – MB3 – PS2 – RB4 – MB4 – PS3 – RB5 – MB5 – PS4 – RB6 – MB6 – PS5 – PS6 – MB7 – PS7 – PS8 – MB8 – JG1<br>
This order is only a suggested progression, and many players may prefer to prioritize the construction of a Jumpgate.<p>
<h3>Destruction of a Moon</h3>
<p>The moon can also be destroyed, which may only occur with the Battle Fortress.</p>
<p>When selecting a Battle Fortress as part of your fleet, Mission selection will include the Mission: 'Destroy'. These missions have low chances of success, and are rarely used except towards the late-game stage. Destroying a moon of a larger diameter requires a significantly larger quantity of Battle Fortresses to obtain comparable chances to destroying a smaller moon.</p>
BODY;
$LNG['questions'][2][4]['title']	= 'Alliance';
$LNG['questions'][2][4]['body']		= <<<BODY
<h3>Forming Alliances and the Alliance Page</h3>
<p>Select "Create Alliance" in the menu "Alliance". Creating an alliance requires a tag (Acronym) of the Alliance and the name of the allaince. After these steps the alliance is created and is associated with your name on the Statistics.</p>
<p>On the alliance page you will find the following links:<br>'List of Members: Here you can see the list of all members with their corresponding information.<br>"Your Rank": This will indicate your rank (and privileges given to you) in the alliance.<br>"Global Message": This function sends a 'circular' message to all members of the alliance, or to members of a rank selected.</p>
<h3>Joining an Alliance</h3>
<p>To join an alliance, click on the alliance tag or name in Galaxy View or Statistics. From here you may send a request (application) to an alliance to join if the alliance is 'open'. Note that alliances make the final verdict on whether to accept or reject applications, and also may have minimum point requirements for new members.</p>
BODY;
